<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-04-26T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-04-26T19:00:00-05:00" n="371" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d371">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">835.2553/4–2650: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                    to the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Argentina</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#left">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                                </seg>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-04-26T19:00:00-05:00">April
                                        26, 1950—7 p. m.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>241. <gloss target="#t_FYI1">FYI</gloss>
                                <gloss target="#t_SONJ1">SONJ</gloss><note n="1" xml:id="d371fn1">Standard Oil of New Jersey.</note> and Cereijo reached
                                agreement Apr 25<note n="2" xml:id="d371fn2">Not printed.</note>
                                providing supply 20, 000 barrels crude daily for 6 months and 10,000
                                to 20,000 barrels fol 6 months at discretion <gloss target="#t_SONJ1">SONJ</gloss>. Agreement previously reached
                                Ultramar providing 5,500 barrels daily for 1 year. Each agreement
                                    payable<note n="3" xml:id="d371fn3">By the Argentine Government:
                                    the oil was to be imported into Argentina under dollar credits
                                    granted by the oil companies themselves.</note> in dols over
                                2-year period. Provision made for early negot long-term agreement.
                                Amer Fon Power offered sell basis one-fourth cash one-half over 10
                                year period one-fourth reinvested. Cereijo countered with one-half
                                reinvested and conversations will continue BAires about May 15.
                                Moving picture cos attempting reach agreement based on various <hi rend="italic">quid pro quos</hi> including local investment
                                one-half earnings but no agreement yet.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>